    covarH: "How variables move together",
    covarIntro: "Axes aren't independent. Picking a value on one usually narrows the plausible range on others — design constraints, economics, and engineering coupling all force correlations. Each card states the <b>mechanism</b>, not just the correlation. Strength: <b>tight</b> = forced (can't decouple cheaply); <b>loose</b> = conventional (an exception is plausible).",
    exampleLabel: "Example:",
    whyBundledLabel: "Why bundled:",
    targetLabel: "Target:",
    exemplarLabel: "e.g.",
    footer: "<b>Caveats.</b> Positions are coarse — coffee brewing has many sub-variants ('pour-over' covers V60, Chemex, Kalita Wave, all subtly different). Distribution shading is illustrative, not measured. Confidence marks: <code>*</code> well-established, <code>~</code> estimated, <code>?</code> guess. Endpoint bundles describe what tends to <em>cluster</em> at each pole, not iron laws — exceptions exist (e.g., AeroPress pressurises lightly without demanding fine grind), and those exceptions are usually worth understanding rather than treated as map flaws.<br><br><b>Source:</b> <a href='https://github.com/ThisIsZeitgeist/dimensional-map' style='color:var(--accent);'>github.com/ThisIsZeitgeist/dimensional-map</a> — MIT licensed.",
